  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\nabla^{T}g=0,\n\\qquad\nT(\\nabla^{T})=0\n\\quad\n(x\\neq p).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nAway from the TZP, the geometry should reduce to ordinary metric-compatible differential geometry. Therefore the Trawinistic connection $\\nabla^{T}$ must satisfy metric compatibility:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\nabla^{T}g=0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\nIt must also be torsion-free away from the degenerate point:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nT(\\nabla^{T})=0,\n\\qquad x\\neq p .\n\\end{equation}\n\nWhen $\\det(g)\\neq 0$, the unique connection satisfying metric compatibility and zero torsion is the Levi-Civita connection. Hence:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\nabla^{T}=\\nabla^{LC},\n\\qquad x\\neq p .\n\\end{equation}\n\nAt $p$, where $\\det(g)|_p=0$, $\\nabla^{T}$ is extended by the rule that null vectors are annihilated or stabilized under the degenerate structure.\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nThe Trawinistic connection preserves ordinary geometry away from $p$ while extending the differential structure into the TZP degeneracy.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
